        {/* BLOCK 1b — AI Mistakes */}
        <div className="mb-8 border-l-4 border-red-600 bg-red-50 p-6">
          <p className="mb-2 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-red-900">
            What most people (and most 'exit to trust' commentary) get wrong about the Division 296 decision
          </p>
          <ul className="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-neutral-900">
            <li>✗ Exit to a family trust is obviously smart if TSB is over $3M — wrong. The Division 296 additional tax is 15% on earnings attributable to the portion above $3M. On a $4M SMSF with 5% earnings, that's about $15,000/year. A trust taxing those same earnings at an average 32-47% marginal rate is $65,000-$94,000/year. The trust environment is worse on earnings tax every single year, and you pay exit tax up-front for the privilege.</li>
            <li>✗ Exit tax is only a problem under 60 — wrong. The 0% tax-free withdrawal for 60+ retired members (s301-10) is a real benefit, but it does not make exit 'free'. The opportunity cost is losing the 15% accumulation or 0% pension phase environment forever. On $4M earning 5% in accumulation, that's $30,000/year of earnings tax vs roughly $65,000+ in a trust — a $35,000/year permanent differential. Tax-free exit is a one-time saving; the earnings environment loss is forever.</li>
            <li>✗ Family trusts have flexible distribution that beats super — misleading. Trusts only achieve low effective rates when income is actually distributed to low-bracket beneficiaries every year. Undistributed trust income is taxed at 47%. If your spouse works, your adult children have jobs, or you simply don't want to gift $50k+ annually to family members, the effective trust rate climbs fast. Super's 15% rate applies uniformly with no distribution requirement.</li>
            <li>✗ You can't stay in super at $3M+ without Div 296 — wrong. Three in-super alternatives address Division 296 without exit tax or losing the super environment: (a) spouse balance equalisation so each member has their own $3M threshold, (b) partial withdrawals to keep TSB under $3M at each 30 June valuation date, (c) the SMSF cost-base reset election (AU-13) which protects pre-2026 embedded gains from Division 296 without requiring exit. These should be modelled first.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

